content.text:
Based on my research, here are three methods to properly implement the Bernino Sans Compressed Extrabold font:

## Method 1: Direct CSS @import (Most Reliable)
```css
@import url('https://use.typekit.net/qes3lop.css');

.severity-header {
    font-family: "jaf-bernino-sans-comp", sans-serif;
    font-weight: 800;
    font-style: normal;
    font-size: 30pt;
    color: rgba(37, 53, 65, 0.9);
}
```

## Method 2: Link tag in HTML + CSS reference
```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://use.typekit.net/qes3lop.css">
```
Then in CSS:
```css
.severity-header {
    font-family: "jaf-bernino-sans-comp", sans-serif;
    font-weight: 800;
    font-style: normal;
}
```

## Method 3: Import the main CSS file that already includes it
```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="css/refactor-ui.css">
```
This would import all styles including the font definition.

**Best Option: Method 1** - Using the @import in the style tag directly in the HTML file, because:
1. It's self-contained and doesn't rely on external CSS files
2. It matches the pattern used in the working CSS file
3. It ensures the font is loaded before being used
4. It uses the exact font-family name that's proven to work in the codebase

The key corrections needed:
- Font-family must be `"jaf-bernino-sans-comp"` (with quotes)
- Font-weight must be `800` for Extrabold
- The @import must be placed at the top of the styles

Would you like me to implement Method 1 in the severity-icons-demo.html file?

